segments.text: and sitting in Dick Hervey's study, getting ready to chat with him about his years here in College Station with former students and helping A&M in many, many ways.
Let's see.
To begin with, in case someone was looking at this and didn't know who you were, would you give a brief biographical review before you came back to A&M after the war?
before I came back after the war.
I enrolled at A&M in 1938.
Grew up where?
Grew up in Rainbow, Texas.
Graduated in high school, class of 38.
Came to A&M in the fall of 38 and graduated in the spring of 42 with a degree in marketing and finance.
Was in the M3 ROTC
Transferred into the Air Force before graduating.
Went into the Air Force the day after I got my degree from A&M, which was May 7th, 16th, 1942.
Went into the Air Force for four years.
Came out of the service in January of 46.
And came to A&M as Executive Secretary of the Association of Foreign Students.
On October the 1st, 1947.
Now, how did they and you link up at that point?
I was a very good friend of E. E. McQuillan, who was the executive director of the association during my days in A&M.
And he decided that he'd move over with the university as director of development.
And when he did that, the position of executive director of the association became open.
I was on his executive board at the time, the youngest member of his board.
And he called me and asked if I wanted to apply for the position, and I said yes.
And I did apply for the position and was given the job.
And so you began, what was the- I began October the 1st, 1947.
Describe the association staff and so forth at that time.
At that time, there were about 10 people on the staff of the association.
We had 40,000 addresses of graduates and former students.
We had a bookkeeper, the director.
The bookkeeper was Mr. Lonnie Locke.
We had a secretary to the executive director.
That was Marie Kalanick.
We had Ms. Woody Mae Shepherd, who was head of the class reunions and class programs.
We had Doris Wren, who worked on records.
And in the mailroom, we had Ms. Helen Price, who is now the wife
former dean of the School of Veterinary Medicine, worked in records.
And we had a little student wife named Higgins, whose husband had played in on the football team.
And that was about it.
Where were we?
We were located in the administration building at the east gate.
As you go up the steps to the back, the first floor,
turn around right to the right, and the first doors on the right was the Former Students Association.
We had two offices, one big central office, my office, and then we had a mailroom office down the hall.
That was the size of it.
And it was officially entitled the same as it is now?
The Association of Former Students, which was named about
Woolen became executive secretary in 1926, and they had a reorganization of the association, and they named it that at that time, in the late 20s.
You mentioned 40,000 names.
Computers weren't around then.
No.
How did y'all have those available?
Our records were all on the dressograph plates.
which I guess was the forerunner of a computer car.
And we had it so set that we could tab it for a contribution or a non-contribution.
We had the class numeral on it.
We had the major course of study, got the degree in veterinary medicine or agriculture or whatever.
And we were doing the best we could with what we had.
And you had also, I presume, some geographic.
So if I wanted everybody from the Dallas area.
They were organized geographically.
Geographically and by class.
So we could pull out cities or counties or states or whatever.
And so that's 1947.
And the president at that time of A&M.
The president, when I went there with Mr. Gibb Gilchrist, we had no chancellor's system.
Describe him.
Mr. Gilchrist was an engineer, graduated the University of Texas in 1909, was a state highway engineer prior to his coming here, and in the mid-30s he was brought here as Dean of Engineering.
He was a very fine, tough administrator.
He was a very good man, though there are a lot of people that might disagree with me a little bit.
He was an outstanding college administrator.
And conducted a real, ran a real good show here as long as he was president and then continued as chancellor.
The chancellorship organization was his idea.
And the chancellor system was put into effect in 1948.
And Mr. Gilchrist became the first chancellor of the A&M system.
And when he became chancellor in 1948, the longtime dean of Bolton, we called him Bear Tracks, became president.
the Gilchrist lived in the old, to you and me, President's House over near Sabeasa?
Yes, yes.
All right, and then when the chancellorship was created, the White House down near the core area?
Yes.
Okay.
Moved into what, what did we call that house?
I forgot, but
Anyway, when he became Chancellor, he moved in that White House.
Mr. Bolton, I don't recall if Mr. Bolton ever moved in the old, what's called, President's Home.
I guess he did.
As president, Gilchrist office, his office was in the, what you and I used to call the system administration building facing east.
Yes, in the system building.
And he remained, his office remained there as chancellor.
Yes.
Where did President Bolton's office?
President Bolton, when was the Koch building built?
I don't know.
Richard Koch building.
I'm trying to think of a minute.
I, as I remember now, I'd have to go back to the date of the, I'll check that in a minute, when the coat building was built.
I'm going to say that Dean Bolton was in the coat building
provided that building was at that time built.
This, remember, was 1948 to 1950.
There was no Memorial Student Center, and I have a feeling there was no boat building at that time.
Mr. Bolton's office would have been in one of the engineering buildings as dean of engineering.
And he may have stayed in that building for a while as president.
Describe, in the late 40s, describe the campus physically.
What buildings were where?
The campus in 1947 to 1950, its parameter was the
Administration building, we called it, on the east gate.
And the west gate was the railroad station.
And to the south was Old Jersey Street.
And to the north gate was the North Gate.
And anything to the west of the campus was very rural.
few residential areas on the south side of the campus.
The north side of the campus was the old North Gate, which was the business section of College Station at the time.
The East Gate was a few residences built there in the late 30s and not much more.
A few
apartments had been moved in from old air bases and army bases and converted to branch student housing.
And they were called College View.
And it was on the area where they now have new student apartments.
And we were in very short supply of branch student housing because most of the veterans, a lot of the veterans,
came back after the war, 46, 47, 48, were married, needed housing.
They converted all the old project houses, which were located on the south side, into apartments.
And they had four apartments in each of those buildings, so they provided some housing.
Were there any trailers?
Yes, there were trailers.
All around the old project houses where students lived.
Where athletic facilities are now.
Where athletic facilities are now, yes.
Who were some of the leading personalities on the campus at that time?
Leading personalities.
Well, of course, Spike White.
and his bunch of student activities were very active.
Mr. Penberg was, or was named, Dean of England.
He was active.
Then in the core, what little core we had in those days was much more than it is now because it was still ushered for incoming students.
was Colonel Stan Malloy, who was a commandant.
Joe Davis, who was a major, worked for Colonel Malloy.
And then there were attack officers like Taylor Wilkins, Charles Taylor,
Howard Perry, Roy Buchek at one time.
And many people of that nature had been in the service and came out and were employed as track officers.
The football team was coached by Coach Homer Norton, whose contract was bought up after the A&M Rice football game in the fall of 1947.
I can tell you about that if you're interested.
Oh, yes.
When our better football players went into the service in 1941, 42, 43, Coach Norton promised those boys that went into the service a scholarship, athletic scholarship when they came back.
Well, when the war was over, most of those young men had not gotten a degree.
So they came back to Indiana and they wanted their athletic scholarship and Coach Norton gave them the scholarship.
And they attempted to play football, but they weren't as good athletically as they had been before the war.
But Coach Norton, for his credit, honored his work and gave every one of those
players, former players, and their scholarships.
As a result, he was limited as to the number of new scholarships he could afford.
As a result, he was not able to win the games with the alumni and others that perhaps thought that he should win.
In the fall of 47, which was my first year back, we were having trouble winning games.
and using a lot of those old veterans.
So the alumni started becoming unrestful about it.
We made rice in Houston that fall.
And as I recall, the store was something like
37 to 12, 37 to 14, something like that.
It was a one-sided story in favor of Bryce.
After the game, my wife and I and Quillen and his wife went to a cocktail party in Houston, and present were some of the staunch Big Aggies like T.F.
Smith, T.W.
Moley,
Jake Hamlin, George G. Smith, and there was a rumble at that party that night about Norton and his head coaching position.
This was a Saturday night afternoon.
The following Monday, the Houston A&M Club met every Monday at noon at the Rice Hotel.
And at that meeting, there was a rumble about buying up Coach Norton's contract.
As I recall, he had about $20,000 of contract left.
That, I think, represented two years of coaching, about $10,000 a year.
So at that meeting, there was a motion
to start the ball rolling to buy up those gardens contracts without any clearance from the university or anybody else.
That's just the way that things happened in those days.
Well, anyway, Mr. Travis Smith, who was class of 98, stood up and said, if you boys are serious about this matter, I'll match you dollar for dollar.
Every dollar you can raise here, I'll just match.
As a result, the ball got to Roland.
And Mr. Smith did honor his situation.

Whatever was raised at that meeting, I don't remember the figure, but it was not $20,000, more like $4,000 or $5,000 raised by the membership of the club, matched by Mr. Smith's money, and then the rest was raised by Dallas and Fort Worth and Beaumont.
And that's the way the matter was raised, where they paid for his contract and they gave him his money and paid him off.
And Mr. Norton took it very well, though he was disappointed of course, but he did accept the money and resigned his position and went to Galveston, Texas and bought a
a motel in Galveston.
And Harry Styler had been brought here as an assistant to Coach Martin.
And the Athletic Council, then after that happened, named Coach Harry Styler as head football coach.
As far as you know, was there any effort by the campus administration to prevent, to stop this or anything?
Not that I heard of it.
Not that I know of.
And the then called Board of Directors, now Regents, they were not involved particularly.
They were not involved particularly, nor was the administration who had been Mr. Gibb and Gail Christie.
Now we did have an athletic director at that time who was Mr. Carmichael, Bill Carmichael.
Mr. Carmichael had an athletic council, as they do now.
And after all this happened, Mr. Norton's contract was paid up.
Then the athletic council sat down and decided they were going to employ as a head coach.
And they employed Harry Steinway, who was here to be our head coach.
And that was his first season would have been.
the year 48, and he posted 48, 49, and 50.
And then you'll remember the problems that Coach Tyler got into, and he was terminated then.
His position here was terminated sometime in the year, early in the year 51.
And I'll tell you that story.
Go ahead, yes, go ahead.

It was customary for the Houston A&M Club to have a banquet each year for the football team and their girlfriends and all the coaches, and that was held in the Shamrock Hotel, which was pretty new, just having opened in 1949.
Well, the year 19 would have been the banquet for the team of 1950.
The banquet was held, I think, in January of the year 51.
Coach Stiler had been in Dallas for a meeting, and he was to fly from Dallas to Houston.
Mr. Ford Munderland was on the plane.
Mr. Munderland was an executive with the American General Life Insurance Company.
Had been a professor here at A&M.
They flew together.
same plane from Dallas to Houston airport.
Upon arrival at Houston airport, Ford invited Harry to ride with him to the Shamrock Hotel.
But when they arrived and got off the airplane, somebody was there to meet Harry Steiner.
And this person that was meeting Harry insisted that Harry go with him
to ride to the Shamrock Hotel.
So he did, and Mr. Munden went by himself to the Shamrock Hotel.
The banquet was delayed and delayed and delayed.
They wouldn't start, they wouldn't start, they wouldn't start.
Finally, word started around that Coach Tyler had been assaulted.
Rumor had it that
Well, all kinds of groups, of all sorts of descriptions.
But it later developed that Coach Steiner had been seen on the side of the wife of this ex-woman and this young lady that worked at the athletic department.
husband just thoroughly gave Coach Snyder a good beating.
And then put him in the car and took him to Shamrock and let him out there in the garage.
And Harry went to the garage and went into the restroom and went to the telephone and called the trainer, Bill Dayton.
Bill Dayton came to the garage and tried to fix Harry up and pretty badly beat him.
And then took him to a motel, I don't know what it's called, it was out on the water drive, Buck Road, Buck Road Motel, Buck Road Inn, I don't know, around that area.
And this is a real long story, but to make it brief, when all this happened, Mr. D.W. Williams was actually the president.
Mr. Williams investigated the case and Coach Steidler denied knowing who assaulted him and would not admit knowing anything about who this person was.
Mr. Williams, as I understood, had an agreement with Steidler that if anything ever came out that he did know
the person who saw it, then the administration would have had his immediate resignation.

Well, this, what happened, one of the Houston newspapers, I don't believe it's in existence now, but one of the Houston newspapers put an investigative reporter on the case and found out the whole story.
And they called Coach Stider to Houston.
said, apologize, but we're running this story the next day.
But he could do nothing but apologize.
And it was run on pay to get an apology.
His daughter came back to campus and went to Mr. Williams' office and told him the whole story.
And that was the end of the story.
And it was very unfortunate, but it
And then he's followed by... Coach Styler had brought in an outstanding guy from California.
He was the most lovable person that you could ever imagine.
Was Harry's line coach.
And his name was Ray George.
Ray George was named head coach.
coached the 51, 52, and 53.
And he was just such a nice guy that he just wasn't tough enough to be a head coach.
And he, that year, 51, he beat Texas here on Powell Hill, 42-21 in the great game.
And by that time,
Dr. Harrington was president and they declared a holiday after that victory.
So then it was Ray George who served through the year 1953 and there was unrest with Ray's ability to coach and so forth.
So they terminated Ray, and they had a big search for a replacement for Ray, which was a rather unfortunate experience, I think that's what happened.
Maybe that was after Bear Bryant left in 57.
But anyway, they employed him.
Dr. Harrington and Mr. W.T.
Daugherty was, I think, the president of the board of directors then, persuaded Coach Bryant to meet him in Dallas in a hotel room.
And they offered him the job as athletic director and head coach at Andy in 54.
Never discussed salary or anything.
He took the job on a handshake and came to A&M as athletic director and head coach.
And you'll remember that great history that Bear Bryant had here.
What was he like to work with for a person in your position?
Bear Bryant was not easy to work with.
He was a little bit difficult to work with.
I did work with Bear, but Bear had to be told if he was going to do something that we were not accustomed to doing, he would have to be told we don't do that and tell him why.
And once he understood why you didn't want to do something that he wanted to do, and he understood why we didn't, then he went along with it.
But he was not a real easy person to deal with, because he had his own ideas of how he wanted things done.
And he came here without knowing much about the traditions of A&M, the real traditions of A&M.
He knew athletics, and he knew it well.
He'd been in Maryland, he'd been in Kentucky, and I assume
Alabama, and he knew how they did things, which were not exactly like we did.
For example, he wanted to have a big homecoming.
And he talked to me about having a big homecoming.
And I said, Barron, we consider every home game a homecoming.
And we have class reunions and so forth on every home game.
We don't want homecomings.
We won't ever get him to be a homecoming.
But all right, if that's the way it is.
And he went along with that.
But Bear was a loner.
He didn't come in here with a big band and a big ball of rock.
He came in here to do one job, have a good football game.
And that was his mission.
That was his purpose.
And he worked night and day.
He worked hard.
He was an outstanding recruiter, but he didn't want anybody's advice how to do it.
He knew how to do it.
And he stayed with his program.
He recruited players that he could win with.
And he would go to A&M meetings, but he would not let any alumni affairs
interfere with his main primary job, coaching the football team.
Now did he ask you and the former student leadership to do anything for him?
Yes.
Yes, he did.
As a matter of fact, when we were put on probation,
would have been in 54 or 55.
Our association of former student council was in session.
And he asked if he could appear before the group, and he said certainly, come right here.
And his opening statement was, when the going gets tough and tough, and he outlined the probation
